  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="eligibility-h2">
    <h2 id="eligibility-h2">OINP Human Capital Priorities Stream — Eligibility 2026</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> You need a valid Express Entry profile, CRS ≥ 400, a Bachelor's degree+, CLB 7+ in all language skills, and 1 year of skilled work experience (NOC TEER 0/1/2/3).
    </div>
    <p>Ontario's OINP searches the Express Entry pool and sends Notifications of Interest (NOIs) to candidates who meet all these criteria: [web:203]</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Valid Express Entry profile</strong> under FSW, CEC, or Federal Skilled Trades Program</li>
      <li><strong>Minimum CRS score of 400</strong> (OINP has lowered this briefly in past draws)</li>
      <li><strong>Education:</strong> Bachelor's, Master's, or PhD — or an ECA showing Canadian equivalency (3-year diplomas do NOT qualify)</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> CLB 7 or higher in all four skills (Speaking, Listening, Reading, Writing)</li>
      <li><strong>Work experience:</strong> Minimum 1 year continuous paid full-time (1,560 hours) in NOC TEER 0/1/2/3 within the past 5 years</li>
      <li><strong>Intention to live in Ontario</strong> (not Quebec)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If you don't yet meet CRS 400, see our <a href="/improve-score">Improve CRS Score guide</a> — improving your IELTS score from CLB 7 to CLB 9 alone can add 40+ points.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="occupations-h2">
    <h2 id="occupations-h2">Ontario Priority Occupations for OINP In-Demand Skills 2026</h2>
    <div class="answer-box">
      <strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Ontario's April 2026 In-Demand Skills draw targeted 39 occupations — primarily Healthcare, Technology, Construction, Manufacturing, and Transportation workers.
    </div>
    <p>The OINP In-Demand Skills Stream targets workers in occupations facing labour shortages in Ontario. Key priority sectors for 2026 include:</p>
    <table class="data-table" aria-label="Ontario priority occupation sectors 2026">
      <thead><tr><th>Sector</th><th>Example Occupations</th><th>NOC TEER</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Healthcare</td><td>Registered nurses, PSWs, medical technologists</td><td>TEER 1/2/3</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Technology</td><td>Software engineers, data analysts, IT systems</td><td>TEER 1/2</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Construction &amp; Trades</td><td>Electricians, plumbers, carpenters</td><td>TEER 2/3</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Manufacturing</td><td>Industrial mechanics, machinists, welders</td><td>TEER 2/3</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Transportation</td><td>Transport truck drivers, heavy equipment operators</td><td>TEER 3</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Food Processing</td><td>Butchers, food processing labourers</td><td>TEER 3/4</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p style="margin-top:10px;font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text-muted);">Source: <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/2026-ontario-immigrant-nominee-program-updates" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ontario.ca OINP 2026 Updates</a>.</p>
    <p>If your occupation isn't listed, try our <a href="/fsw-calculator">FSW Points Calculator</a> or <a href="/cec-calculator">CEC Calculator</a> for federal Express Entry pathways, or the <a href="/alberta-crs-calculator">Alberta CRS Calculator</a> if you're open to settling in Alberta.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="faq-h2">
    <h2 id="faq-h2">Frequently Asked Questions — Ontario CRS Calculator</h2>
    <div id="faqAccordion">

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq1">What is a good CRS score for Ontario Express Entry 2026?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq1">For OINP Human Capital Priorities Stream, you need a minimum CRS of 400. However, OINP typically sends NOIs to candidates with CRS scores between 400–540. To be competitive for federal all-program draws (CRS ~490–520 in 2026), aim for 500+.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq2">How many CRS points does an Ontario nomination give?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq2">An Ontario OINP provincial nomination adds +600 federal CRS points. PNP-only federal draws in 2026 have had cutoffs around 786–802 — well covered when you combine even a modest base CRS score with the +600 bonus.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq3">What is the minimum CRS score for OINP Human Capital Priorities?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq3">The minimum CRS is 400 for the OINP Human Capital Priorities Stream. Ontario has occasionally lowered this threshold during targeted draws, but 400 is the published baseline requirement per the official Ontario.ca eligibility page.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq4">Can I apply to OINP without a job offer?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq4">Yes. The OINP Human Capital Priorities Stream does NOT require a job offer. You simply need a valid Express Entry profile meeting education, language, and work experience criteria. However, job offers are required for the Employer Job Offer streams and In-Demand Skills Stream.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq5">Is this Ontario CRS calculator accurate?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq5">This tool uses official IRCC CRS scoring criteria and provides a close estimate. For your exact score, always verify with the <a href="https://www.ircc.canada.ca/english/immigrate/skilled/crs-tool.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official IRCC CRS tool</a> and check <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/ontarios-express-entry-human-capital-priorities-stream" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official OINP eligibility requirements</a>.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="faq6">How can I improve my CRS score for Ontario?<span class="faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a" id="faq6">Top strategies: (1) Retake IELTS/CELPIP — improving from CLB 7 to CLB 9 adds ~40 points; (2) Gain Canadian work experience — each additional year adds 10–20 points; (3) Add French language skills (+25 to +50 pts); (4) Complete a Canadian degree (+15 to +30 pts). See all 10 strategies in our <a href="/improve-score">Improve CRS Score guide</a>.</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" aria-labelledby="tools-h2">
    <h2 id="tools-h2">Related CRS Calculators &amp; Ontario Immigration Tools</h2>
    <p>Explore these free tools for other Express Entry programs and provincial streams:</p>
